Tests of the Proposal 

As explained earlier, on the SYM side of our proposed correspondence 
we must use the -BMN operator basis. For BMN operators with 
2 scalar impurities this basis was
constructed in to order  and
 and involves a linear combination
of the original single-trace BMN operator and the double-trace 
(in general multi-trace)
BMN operators.

SYM predictions 

All the currently known SYM results for 3-point BMN correlators can be 
divided into two
broad classes. The first class  involves 1 general and 2 chiral 
-BMN operators 
(i.e. 1 string and 2 supergravity states). Furthermore, 
no flavour-changing processes
are allowed for the 3-point functions of the first class.
The second class  involves 2 general
-BMN operators (i.e. 2 string states and 
1 supergravity state) with or without
flavour changing, and the flavour changing 1 string  2 supergravity processes.

The 3-point functions of the first class can be calculated directly 
with the original
single-trace BMN operators since it is easy to check that the contributions 
coming from the
double-trace operators vanish (at the first non-vanishing order in ). 
Three-point functions
of the first class were calculated in for 2 scalar impurities and, in
the follow-up paper
, for 3 scalar impurities at the leading non-trivial order in .
For the second class the contributions from the double-trace operators are 
important and one should use the -BMN basis. The calculations 
of the 3-point functions 
in this basis with 2 scalar impurities were carried out in.

All the currently known
SYM results for 3-point correlators with 2 scalar impurities can be 
summarized by
the following expression for the 3-point function coefficients :
C( k_n l_-n , vac  i_m j_-m )  =
C_123 ^vac 2^2(m y) y ^2 (m^2-n^2/y^2)^2 
